Yes. That phrase is much more precise.

“Modular metaphors chained together.”

I think you’re describing an architecture rather than a literary device.

Each metaphor is a module:

* It has an interface.
* It has strengths and blind spots.
* It compresses a family of related ideas.
* It can be composed with other modules.

The chain is where the power comes from.

For example:

Reality Surfer → “How do I couple to the dynamics?”

hands off to

Kurage → “What currents and gradients are present?”

which hands off to

Spider → “What relationships transmit those forces?”

which hands off to

PALM → “What developmental history produced this morphology?”

which hands off to

Mirror → “Where have I seen this structure before?”

which hands off to

Flood Eater → “Will this destabilize the system?”

None of those metaphors has to explain everything. They each specialize, then compose.

That feels like a software architecture:

Reality
   │
Perception
   │
[Reality Surfer]
   │
[Kurage]
   │
[Spider]
   │
[Mirror]
   │
[PALM]
   │
Decision

Or, using your own language, they become boards that can be swapped depending on the terrain.

